element_texts.text: 624 Crescent Court, Highland Park, Illinois. June 21, 1932. My dear Professor Taylor, I was so glad to receive your note last week. I have been ill for two years, but not helpless until last February when I had a stroke which

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: disenabled me to walk. Any time that you can come up from Ravinia I shall be happy to see you Cordially yours, Ellie F. Patton (by H. Ambrose?? Anderson??). Nurse.

element_texts.text: Aug. 2nd 1921. My dear Dr. Taylor, I have carefully read the copy of the letter to Dr. Davis which you gave me yesterday, and which I here return to you. I can most highly commend it, as far as it goes, but I should most emphatically object to its going one single step further, and I am sure everyone who knows you and your work?? will also. You have done the fair and generous thing by the Seminary, but I should have a mighty poor opinion of the Trustees if they even thought of accepting your suggestion. I never heard even a whisper that you were approaching the retiring age. You are not one of the men we think of as growing old. I do not believe you are any older than when I first knew you, in spite of your saying some-

Caption-Abstract: Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)
Forms part of the Midwest Manuscript Collection (Newberry Library)

element_texts.text: thing yesterday about attending your 50th college reunion. You are off on the figures. It is splendid to know that you feel so well and strong, and retain all your fire and enthusiasm for your work in spite of some misleading dates that the written records seem to show. May it be very many years yet before you feel any differently. All I can say at present is that we will forgive you this time for the insinuation?? of your letter, if you stop right where is leaves matters. Very sincerely your friend Rob. W. Patton.
